english:
  title: A Response to Spiritual Master's Letter
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow my head in humble reply. Last September, when the esteemed Master from the Dharma Academy arrived, I received your letter of encouragement and teaching, complete in its warmth and care. Day after day I wished to return your kindness with a response, yet my nature has never favored swift correspondence, and so I have delayed until now—my shame knows no bounds.

    I have long observed the writings of others, yet have never dared presume to inscribe my comments upon them. When your letter mentioned this scroll-text, I could not fathom what you had seen or what words I supposedly inscribed. Could it be that some vulgar person falsely claimed my name and composed these remarks?

    Since the Jin and Song dynasties, many Buddhist monks have sought renown through verse, yet in their writings—though some shine with brilliance—none have plumbed the depths of their craft's true source. This is because the art of comparison and evocation differs from the craft of composition itself. Thus even among us Confucian scholars, few can master both; how much less the monks? If our Master truly accomplishes this, his virtue far exceeds the ordinary.

    Regarding what the world calls a "true scholar"—I wish to clarify this matter. The so-called great scholars of our age are merely those skilled at textual minutiae who pass the civil examinations. If this alone makes one a great scholar, why then are they not legion? Yet such rarity has not been seen even in ancient times. Consider Jia Yi, Sima Qian, Han Yu, Liu Zongyuan—these few stand apart. Even in the flourishing ages of Han and Tang, their exceptional deeds remain few and conspicuous. In more recent times came Ouyang Xiu, who championed ancient prose and opposed lesser schools, earning him the title "modern Han Yu." Wang Anshi illuminated the sage's way through studying the classics, and Su Shi, encompassing the hundred schools, penetrated to the very root of composition—these were true great scholars.

    Those who bear the name of great scholar without its substance are thieves of our Way and count among its sinners. I confess I have no desire to become such. Should anyone bestow such a title upon me, I shall respectfully decline with bowed head, unable and unwilling to accept it. I earnestly beg you speak of this no more.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jia Yi, Sima Qian, Han Yu, and Liu Zongyuan represent the author's ideal of genuine scholars whose accomplishments transcended mere technical mastery.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'comparison and evocation' (比興) refers to poetic techniques, contrasted here with scholarly composition and intellectual inquiry.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to recent worthies—Ouyang Xiu, Wang Anshi, and Su Shi—reflects Lim Chun's conception of true learning as integrating both textual scholarship and moral philosophy.
